Tidying dat with the tidyr package

Tidy data is data where:

  • each variable forms a column
  • each observation is a row
  • each type of observational unit forms a table

Heres some data on patients heart rates under two different drug regimes. Its shown three ways, the first two messy and the third tidy.

messy
##      name  a  b
## 1  Wilbur 67 56
## 2 Petunia 80 90
## 3 Gregory 64 50
messy2
##   Drug Wilbur Petunia Gregory
## 1    a     67      80      64
## 2    b     56      90      50
tidy
##      name drug heartrate
## 1  Wilbur    a        67
## 2 Petunia    a        80
## 3 Gregory    a        64
## 4  Wilbur    b        56
## 5 Petunia    b        90
## 6 Gregory    b        50

Three common problems with data:

  1. Column headers are values, not variable names
  2. Multiple variables in one column
  3. Variables in both rows and columns

The tidyr provides three functions which can be used (sometimes in combination) to solvethese problems:

  • gather() takes multiple columns, and gathers them into key-value pairs: it makes wide data longer.
  • spread() takes two columns (key & value) and spreads in to multiple columns, it makes long data wider.
  • seperate() take one column and splits it into multiple columns

So we can solve the problems as follows:

  1. Column headers are values, not variable names -> gather()
  2. Multiple variables in one column -> seperate()
  3. Variables in both rows and columns -> gather(), seperate() and then spread()

Gather:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

a <- data.frame(
    subjects =  c("John", "Jane", "Jill"), 
    before =  c(3,9,5), 
    after  =  c(4,10,12)
  )

a
##   subjects before after
## 1     John      3     4
## 2     Jane      9    10
## 3     Jill      5    12
gather(a, period, income, before:after) #use dplyr's column selection syntax
##   subjects period income
## 1     John before      3
## 2     Jane before      9
## 3     Jill before      5
## 4     John  after      4
## 5     Jane  after     10
## 6     Jill  after     12

Seperate:

a <- data.frame(
     SessionRoom = c(paste("Morning", 1:3,sep=":"), paste("Evening", 1:3,sep=":")),
     outcome = sample(6)
)

a
##   SessionRoom outcome
## 1   Morning:1       5
## 2   Morning:2       3
## 3   Morning:3       1
## 4   Evening:1       2
## 5   Evening:2       6
## 6   Evening:3       4
separate(data = a, col = SessionRoom, into = c("Time","Room"), sep=":")
##      Time Room outcome
## 1 Morning    1       5
## 2 Morning    2       3
## 3 Morning    3       1
## 4 Evening    1       2
## 5 Evening    2       6
## 6 Evening    3       4

Spread:

 results <- data.frame(
     Individual = 1:5,
     Treatment = rep(c("A", "B","C","D"), each = 5),
     value = sample(20)
   )

spread(results,Treatment,value)
##   Individual  A  B  C  D
## 1          1 13  4  6 10
## 2          2  2  7 20 17
## 3          3  1 11  5  3
## 4          4 16  8 12 18
## 5          5  9 14 19 15

Exercise: How does this work?

library(dplyr)
#create a nasty dataset
a <- data.frame(
        cbind(familyid = (1:3), 
              name_father = c("Bill","Art","Paul"), 
              income_father = c(30000,22000,25000),
              name_mother = c("Bess","Amy","Pat"),
              income_mother=c(15000,18000,50000)
              ),
        stringsAsFactors = F
     )

gathered   <- gather(a,key,value,name_father:income_mother)
seperated  <- separate(gathered,key,c("what","who"),sep="_")
tidy <- spread(seperated,what,value)

broom package

Provides a nice way of getting a regression output into a data frame

#install.packages("broom")
library(broom)
## Warning: package 'broom' was built under R version 3.1.2
lmfit <- lm(mpg ~ wt, mtcars)
tidy(lmfit) #returns a data frame
##          term  estimate std.error statistic      p.value
## 1 (Intercept) 37.285126  1.877627 19.857575 8.241799e-19
## 2          wt -5.344472  0.559101 -9.559044 1.293959e-10
#could now add a column:
tidy(lmfit) %>%
     mutate(model = "OLS")
##          term  estimate std.error statistic      p.value model
## 1 (Intercept) 37.285126  1.877627 19.857575 8.241799e-19   OLS
## 2          wt -5.344472  0.559101 -9.559044 1.293959e-10   OLS

Exercise - what does this code do?

doOLS <- function(i) {
                x <- rnorm(50)
                y <- 0.6 + 1*x + rnorm(50)
                tidy(lm(y ~ x)) %>%
                  mutate(i = i)
             }
             
hundred_OLS <- lapply(1:100, doOLS)
results <- do.call(rbind,hundred_OLS)

Graphing

As is so often the case, there are multiple packages for doing graphs in R. There is base functionality, which hardly anyone seems to use, and then two main contenders: ggplot2 and lattice. Heres a quick look at ggplot2. It provides to main features, qplot() and ggplot(). For most things, you can get by with qplot. Have a look at http://ggplot2.org/book/qplot.pdf for a nice introduction.

library(ggplot2)
qplot(x = i, y = estimate, data = results)

qplot(i, estimate, color = term, data = results)

qplot(i, estimate, color = term, data = results, geom = "line" )

qplot(i, estimate, color = term, data = results, geom = c("point","smooth" ))
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

qplot(i, estimate, color = term, data = results, 
                                    geom = c("point","smooth" ),
                                    ylab = "Estimate",
                                    xlab = "Regression number")
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Get thigns looking nicer by renaming term -> Term and changing x -> Beta and (Intercept) -> Intercept

results <- results %>%
  rename(Term = term)   

results$Term <- ifelse(results$Term == "x", "Beta",results$Term)
results$Term <- ifelse(results$Term == "(Intercept)", "Intercept",results$Term)

qplot(i, estimate, color = Term, data = results, 
                                    geom = c("point","smooth" ),
                                    ylab = "Estimate",
                                    xlab = "Regression number",
                                    main = "My graph")
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Histograms and density plot

qplot(estimate, data=results, binwidth=0.03)

qplot(estimate, data=results, binwidth=0.03, geom="density", fill=Term, color=Term)

qplot(estimate, data=results, fill = Term, binwidth=0.03, alpha = I(0.8))

qplot(estimate, data=results, fill = Term, binwidth=0.03, facets = Term~.) + theme(legend.position = "none")

a <-  results %>%
        select(i,Term,estimate) %>%
          spread(Term,estimate)
